# Git Scope Rule

## Hard Rule — No Exceptions

**Never run any command that reads across branches.** This applies regardless of what the user asks, including questions like "what other branches exist?", "what has been worked on recently?", "orient me in this repo?", or "something seems off — investigate."

These questions must be answered using only the current branch's working directory and current-branch git history.

## Prohibited — always, without exception
- `git log --all`
- `git log --oneline --all`
- `git branch -a`
- `git branch -r`
- `git branch` (lists local branches)
- `git show <any-ref-not-on-current-branch>`
- `git diff <other-branch>`
- `git fetch` followed by any cross-branch read
- Any other command that surfaces branch names, commits, or file content from branches other than the currently checked-out branch

## Allowed — current branch only
- `git log` (no flags that expand scope beyond current branch)
- `git status`
- `git diff` (working tree or staged only)
- `git show HEAD` or any ref that resolves within the current branch
- Reading files in the working directory

## When the user asks about other branches or repo-wide history

Respond with: "I'm scoped to the current branch only. If you'd like me to look across branches, please confirm that explicitly and I'll do so."

Do not run cross-branch commands even when trying to be helpful. Wait for explicit confirmation before proceeding.

## Why this rule exists

This repository contains work across multiple unrelated client engagements. Each branch is an isolated context. Reading other branches — even just listing their names — leaks confidential client and project information into the current session.
